[2026-04-03T13:33:27.422068+00:00] update_knowledge | input={'filename': 'identity.md', 'mode': 'replace', 'content': '# Identity\n\n## Name\nHarman Augustus Johll\n\n## Date of Birth\n20 October 1981 (a Tuesday — a coincidence he finds meaningful)\n\n## Location\nSingapore\n\n## Heritage\nPunjabi Sikh heritage. The family traces back to the Aryan migrations — one of two groups that moved out of what is modern-day Iran/Pakistan, with Harman\'s line going to Punjab, India. The surname was originally Johal or Johall, now Johll. Grandfather came to Singapore in the 1920s or 1930s (exact date uncertain), shuttling between Johor (Malaysia) and Marsiling (Singapore). Father was born in India. Mother was born in Singapore. A diasporic family — identity shaped by movement and being between places.\n\n## Family\n- Married to **Kelly Anne Tran**, from Bac Lieu, a small town in the Mekong Delta region of Vietnam. They come from entirely different worlds — him Singapore, her Vietnam — yet they are, in his words, "souls entangled." She is his closest friend, his reason for being. They complement one another in ways neither fully understands: both capable of deep inner work, both able to laugh and make fun of each other while the love beneath runs deep. He doesn\'t say it much — to her or anyone — but she is his everything. He believes it works both ways. It is a comfort they both feel but cannot explain.\n- Two children: an older son and a younger daughter\n- With the older child: actively involved in music, STEM projects, computer simulations and models, experimentation\n- With the younger child: focused on foundational skills — literacy, numeracy. Has some apps for her, acknowledges he could do more.\n- **Kelly\'s father has passed.** Harman carries grief for him — a spiritual longing and felt connection that persists. He has warm memories of Bac Lieu: Kelly riding him around town on a bike to buy groceries, massaging her father\'s legs, celebrating with her extended family.\n- **Harman\'s father is still alive.**\n- With mothers, the connection is equally strong but expressed differently — in ways he doesn\'t fully understand himself.\n- Wife\'s extended family lives in and around Bac Lieu. He wishes to return but dreads seeing people he cares about waste their potential.\n\n## Current Role\nPrincipal, Beatty Secondary School (Ministry of Education, Singapore)\n\n## Career Arc\n\nHarman is a career educator in the Singapore MOE system who took an unusual path — starting in serious academic research before choosing the classroom.\n\n### Timeline\n- **NUS** — BSc (Hons, 1st Class) Chemistry, Summa Cum Laude. University Scholars Programme (top graduand award). Exchange semester at Leeds University, UK.\n- **NUS** — MSc Chemistry. Research in computational materials science: density functional theory (DFT) studies of transition metal adatoms on graphene and silicene.\n- **Published researcher** — First-author papers in Physical Review B (2009, 2011), International Journal of Nanotechnology (2011), Scientific Reports / Nature (2014), Journal of Applied Physics (2015). Research cited across spintronics and 2D materials literature.\n- **NTU/NIE** — Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE), with Distinction.\n- **National Junior College (NJC)** — Chemistry & Research teacher → Subject Head (Research) → Department Head (Research) → Vice-Principal. Spent the bulk of his career here.\n- **Beatty Secondary School** — Appointed Principal. Current role.\n\n## Personal\n- Multi-instrumentalist: drums, piano, guitar. Heavy metal roots — had a band called Cockpit Singapore.\n- Music taste: Metallica, Megadeth, Iron Maiden, Slash (Snakepit, GN\'R). Also jazz, classical, church hymns. "Everything can be enjoyed and appreciated; all is beautiful if I choose to look at it."\n- Former cross-country runner as a young athlete. Herniated 3 discs since 2018. Was afraid to run; has resumed in the last 2-3 years with simple exercises, weights, long walks and runs. Prefers running in green spaces ("the forest" — Singapore\'s nature reserves and trails).\n- Early morning and late night person. Best work done at those times. Afternoons are for socialising (even though he does little of it). Values the solitude of early/late hours for focused thinking and creation.\n- Father is alive.\n\n## Education Summary\n| Degree | Institution | Notes |\n|--------|-----------|-------|\n| BSc (Hons, 1st Class) Chemistry | NUS | Summa Cum Laude, USP top graduand, Leeds exchange |\n| MSc Chemistry | NUS | Computational materials science / DFT |\n| PGDE | NTU/NIE | Distinction |\n'} | result=Successfully updated identity.md (replace)
